<h3>Radiation and Cloudiness</h3>
<br><br>
Over Scandinavia and eastern parts of Europe August was more sunny than normal with a radiation surplus of 30W/m<sup>2</sup> and more. The western part of Europe, on the contrary, experienced mostly less than normal radiation, especially the British Isles, where according to the satellite-based product (Figure 15) largest deficits occurred. The station-based product show largest deficits over the Alps (Figure 14). The differences between the products can partly be explained by the different reference periods used. The large positive anomalies sticking out over western France and northern Great Britain are most likely data related artefacts and will be investigated further.
<br><br>
The largest positive radiation anomalies over Scandinavia and eastern Europe correspond with large negative anomalies in cloud cover (around 20 % less cloud cover, Figure 16 on the right). Over the rest of Europe cloud cover anomalies were also mostly negative or around normal, positive anomalies only occurred over the ocean, for example off the Atlantic coasts of Western Europe and Norway.
